            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "1.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " That the Levites engaged in the choral service were regarded as those especially who prayed \"for the life of the king and of his sons\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 6:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " That the singing Levites who returned from Babylon, being so few in number (128), had to be constantly on duty in the temple, and so needed a regular daily stipend. The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "nexus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of this verse with the preceding one imp!ice that the payment in question was an important part of the internal business of the house committed to Uzzi. Nehemiah 11:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And the overseer (chief) of the Levites at Jerusalem was Uzzi, the son of Bani, of the sons of Asaph, the singers, in the business of the house of God. The מלאכה of the house of God was the duty of the Levites of the house of Shemaiah, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Hence the remark in the present verse is supplementary to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The chiefs or presidents of the two other divisions of Levites - of those to whom the outward business was entrusted, and of the singers - are named in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; while, in the case of those entrusted with the business of the house of God, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the chiefs are not named, probably because they were over the singers, the sons of Asaph, who in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " had not as yet been named. This is therefore done afterwards in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". מלאכת לנגד, coram opere, i.e., circa ea negotia, quae coram in templo exigenda erant (Burm. in Ramb.), does not belong to המּשׁררים, but to הלויּם פּקיד: Uzzi was overseer of the Levites in respect of their business in the house of God, i.e., of those Levites who had the charge of this business. The reason of this is thus given in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : \"for a command of the king was over them, and an ordinance was over the singers concerning the matter of every day.\" עליהם refers to the Levites. \"A command of the king was over them\" means: the king had commanded them. This command was concerning בּיומו יום דּבר, the matter of every day. The words stand at the end of the verse, because they refer to the two subjects המּלך and אמנה. אמנה is an arrangement depending upon mutual agreement, a treaty, an obligation entered into by agreement; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 10:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The meaning of the verse is: The every-day matter was laid upon the Levites by the command of the king, upon the singers by an agreement entered into. בּיומו יום דּבר, pensum quotidianum, is correctly explained by Schmid: de rebus necessariis in singulos dies. That we are not to understand thereby the contribution for every day, the rations of food (Ramb., Berth.), but the duty to be done on each day, is obvious from the context, in which not provisions, but the business of the Levites, is spoken of; and Uzzi the Asaphite was placed over the Levites in respect of their business in the house of God, and not in respect of food and drink. The business of the Levites in the house of God was determined by the command of the king; the business of the singers, on the contrary, especially that one of the singers should exercise a supervision over the services of the Levites in worship, was made the matter of an אמנה, an agreement entered into among themselves by the different divisions of Levites. The king is not David, who once regulated the services of the Levites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 23:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".), but the Persian king Artaxerxes, who is mentioned as המּלך in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and המּלך מצות undoubtedly refers to the full power bestowed by Artaxerxes upon Ezra to order all that concerned the worship of God at Jerusalem; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]